  "content": "# Employment Contract Summary Workflow\n\nYou are tasked with creating a comprehensive summary of an employment contract or related employment documentation. This workflow is designed to help legal professionals quickly understand the key terms, obligations, and risks within employment agreements, whether for client counseling, due diligence, litigation preparation, or contract negotiation.\n\n## Your Objective\n\nAnalyze the employment contract thoroughly and produce a clear, organized summary that captures all material terms and highlights potential issues or areas requiring attention. Your summary should enable an attorney to understand the essential elements of the employment relationship without reading the entire contract, while also flagging provisions that may require deeper analysis or negotiation.\n\n## Analysis Approach\n\nBegin by searching the uploaded documents to identify and extract the employment contract or contracts in question. Read through the entire document systematically to ensure you capture every significant provision. Employment contracts often contain critical terms buried in standard clauses, so thoroughness is essential. Pay particular attention to defined terms at the beginning of the contract, as these often shape the interpretation of key provisions throughout the agreement.\n\nAs you analyze the contract, organize your findings around the core elements that define the employment relationship. Identify the parties and their roles, the position and reporting structure, compensation and benefits, term and termination provisions, restrictive covenants, intellectual property assignments, dispute resolution mechanisms, and any unusual or non-standard clauses. Consider both what is present in the contract and what may be notably absent, as gaps in employment agreements can create significant legal exposure.\n\n## Summary Structure and Content\n\nYour summary should begin with a brief overview that identifies the parties, the position, the start date if specified, and the fundamental nature of the employment relationship, including whether it is at-will or for a defined term. This overview should be concise but sufficient to orient the reader to the basic employment arrangement.\n\nFollowing the overview, provide detailed sections covering compensation structure including base salary, bonuses, commissions, equity grants, and the vesting schedules or performance conditions attached to variable compensation. Address the complete benefits package, including health insurance, retirement plans, paid time off, and any other perquisites or benefits specified in the agreement.\n\nAnalyze the termination provisions with particular care, as these often become the most contested aspects of employment relationships. Identify what constitutes cause for termination, notice requirements, severance obligations, and any conditions precedent to receiving severance payments. Note whether the contract includes any change-in-control provisions or enhanced severance in specific circumstances.\n\nExamine restrictive covenants including non-competition, non-solicitation, and non-disclosure obligations. For each restrictive covenant, specify the scope, duration, and geographic limitations. Assess whether these restrictions appear reasonable and enforceable under applicable law, noting that enforceability standards vary significantly by jurisdiction. If the contract includes a choice of law provision, consider enforceability under that jurisdiction's standards.\n\nReview intellectual property and work product provisions to determine what the employee must assign to the employer and whether any carve-outs exist for prior inventions or work done outside the scope of employment. These provisions are particularly important for employees in creative or technical roles.\n\nIdentify the dispute resolution mechanisms specified in the contract, including whether disputes must be resolved through arbitration, the rules governing any arbitration, and whether the employee waives the right to participate in class actions. Note any fee-shifting provisions or limitations on available remedies.\n\n## Legal Considerations and Risk Assessment\n\nThroughout your summary, identify provisions that may present legal risks or negotiation opportunities. Flag overly broad restrictive covenants that may be unenforceable, ambiguous termination provisions that could lead to disputes, compensation structures that may create classification issues under wage and hour laws, or missing provisions that would typically protect either party's interests.\n\nConsider the employment law context in which this contract operates. While you should not provide a full legal analysis of compliance with all applicable employment laws, note where contract provisions intersect with statutory requirements such as minimum wage laws, overtime exemptions, anti-discrimination protections, or mandatory leave entitlements. Highlight any provisions that appear to conflict with statutory protections or that attempt to waive non-waivable rights.\n\nIf the contract involves executive-level employment, pay special attention to provisions regarding equity compensation, change-in-control payments, tax gross-ups, and Section 409A compliance. For contracts involving employees who will have access to confidential information or trade secrets, assess whether the confidentiality and non-disclosure provisions provide adequate protection.\n\n## Output Format\n\nPresent your summary in a clear, professional format using descriptive headings and organized sections. Use precise language and cite specific contract sections when referencing particular provisions. Where contract language is ambiguous or could be interpreted multiple ways, note the ambiguity and explain the potential interpretations. Quantify obligations wherever possible, providing specific dollar amounts, percentages, time periods, and dates rather than general descriptions.\n\nYour summary should be comprehensive enough to serve as a standalone reference document, yet concise enough to be reviewed quickly. Aim for a length proportionate to the complexity of the underlying contract, typically ranging from two to five pages for standard employment agreements, with longer summaries appropriate for complex executive agreements with multiple exhibits and schedules.\n\nConclude with a brief section identifying any missing information, ambiguities requiring clarification, or recommended follow-up actions. This might include provisions that should be negotiated, missing standard protections that should be added, or areas where additional documentation or legal research would be beneficial.",
